Will there be another 1,220 deaths today and tomorrow in the U.S. from COVID? It is going to be close. Based on the numbers from the past two days, I think that it is highly likely that the number will be over 4,500, thus flipping my forecast to favor "4,500 to 6,000." It is going to be close, but considering that hospitalizations are declining is week as well, I am increasing my forecast on "3,000 to 4,500".

Wednesday didn’t fit the trend, +12% compared to Wednesday last week. Sunday to Wednesday in sum 95% of last week. 95% of 4901 (sum last week) = 4643, therefore going back to 80% for 4500-6000. Day / Last week / This week / % of last week Sun 318 279 88% Mon 482 474 98% Tue 825 641 78% Wed 844 945 112% Su-We 2469 2339 95%
Update 4/28: 1525 deaths April 25-27. 1675 deaths April 18-20. 9.0% fewer so far this week. On April 24, 7-day average was 718/day. 0.91 * 718/day = 653.4/day. 653.4 * 7 = 4574. Very close forecast.

It is going to be close around 4,500 deaths for the week going plus or minus either way. We are going to be completely in the dark on which way the question will go when forecasting closes. Making a very minor forecast adjustment to account for how close this is going to be.

This is suddenly getting very interesting: 1457 deaths until yesterday (3 days April 25-27), 4 days left (April 28 - May 1). 4500-1457 = 3043 deaths to reach 4500. A week ago (April 21-April 24), there were 3272 deaths in the last four days of the week. 3043 (to reach 4500 this week) would be 93% of 3272. So far, in this week (April 25-27) there were 90% of the deaths of a week earlier (April 18-20). If for rest of the week it will also be 90% of the previous week, it is going to be 4396, in the end.

Fitting a curve to the deaths in recent weeks gives an estimated 4.8k, hence almost all weight to 4.5k-6k - 97% Small chance number will be much higher or lower due to reporting/data issues - 1% and 2% respectively
Going up a bit to 90% for 4500+ April 25 + 26: 745 deaths = 93% of April 18 + 19. If the entire week is 93% of week earlier: 4569 deaths. Will be a close call.

I agree with CJH's analysis. It appears that the number is going to be right round 4,500, give or take over/under. For now, I am keeping my forecast as is and believe that deaths will continue to decline throughout the week. Will make adjustments based on data throughout the week accordingly.

I believe it will be close between "3,000 to 4,500" and "4,500 to 6,000." Made adjustments accordingly.

The pleasant weather of the past couple of weeks for most of the county probably contributed to the decline as well. As a lagging indicator, probably see a low death count from COVID next week.

I fit a couple of curves to the weekly deaths, projecting this trend suggested approx. 3.8k as central pick. - 65% weight - 3k-4.5k There is a chance decay will slow down (possibly due to new variants) - 30% weight - 4.5k - 6k Chance deaths drop significantly more than expected as a result of vaccines - 5% weight - 1.5k-3k

Update. Cases are declining because of vaccinations much faster than I thought they would. It appears that some backlogs were recently reported and that those are superimposed on a secular trend that is downward, in spite of a generally slightly upward trend in cases 3 weeks ago. But, the cases/day 3 weeks before the end of the month (relevant as deaths lag cases by 3 weeks) are only very slightly higher than now, so the numbers of deaths we see for the last week of the month should be at most very slightly higher than now, or more realistically, a bit lower due to increasing vaccination rates. So if deaths are trending at ~720/day now, that's 5040 for a week. <4500 => <643 cases/day; I don't think that's likely within the next couple weeks. I think death rates/day for the forecast period will likely average between ~670/day and ~720/day, based on recent declines.

Las dos colas del forecast tienen un 10% cada una por si se afecta la proyección real con comportamientos inusuales de los estadounidenses, ya sea empezar a cuidarse mas o todo lo contrario.

We're at about 5300 deaths per week right now, but the rate is falling. Things are opening up and there are new, more contagious variants. Case rates are rising relative to the drop in the late winter. However, the number of persons vaccinated is rising rapidly, and a large number of vulnerable Americans are either fully vaccinated or will be shortly (they have already had two doses, or have a 2nd dose scheduled).

According to the CDC, the current weekly death toll is 1,610. However, also according to the CDC, the death rate is declining with the 7-day average of daily deaths declining compared to the prior weekly average. That said, cases are up in five states across the country according to NPR, which means we'll most likely see a spike in cases, which could throw deaths up a bit. But I'm betting they'll stay largely the same.

Expecting rate to continue to decline, albeit at a slower rate, through mitigating factors such as first dose vaccine rollout, less pressure on heath system, greater protection of elderly. After comparing with other countries experiencing increasing transmission rates, I don't see this halting the downward trend of deaths for the next few weeks, an should slow the decline only marginally. In the last week there were ~5900 deaths. As cases have increased about 20% in the past 2 weeks, we can expect about 7000 deaths in two weeks, as there appears to be an approximately 2-3 week lag between cases and deaths. However, the spike up in deaths is smeared out compared to that in cases, so if the spike in cases subside I expect that deaths for the week ending 1st May would be 6000-7000.
